---
import Page from "../layouts/Page.astro";
import CallToAction from "../components/CallToAction.astro";
---

<Page
  title="Features — Formspec"
  description="Everything complex forms require — from calculated fields and conditional logic to multi-step wizards, structured validation, and bidirectional data mapping."
>
  <article class="features">

    <!-- ─── Page Header ─── -->
    <header class="features-header">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">What's included</div>
      <h1>Everything complex forms require.</h1>
      <p class="features-lead">
        Formspec covers the full form lifecycle — from first render to final export — with nothing bolted on.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- ─── BLUF Table ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Requirements checklist</div>
      <h2>Bottom line up front</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        If you're evaluating form tools, here's the direct answer to the most common requirements.
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="bluf-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Requirement</th>
              <th>What Formspec provides</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Calculated fields that update in real time</td>
              <td>61 built-in functions, decimal-precision math, named variables — no code</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Show/hide fields based on other answers</td>
              <td><code>relevant</code> bind with full expression support; cascades to all children</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Required fields that depend on other answers</td>
              <td><code>required</code> bind — a FEL expression, not just a checkbox</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Cross-field validation with custom error messages</td>
              <td>Named shapes: composable rules with error/warning/info severity</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Multi-step wizard navigation</td>
              <td>Wizard, tabs, and single-page modes built in</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Repeatable sections (add/remove rows)</td>
              <td>Repeatable groups and nested repeats with min/max cardinality</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Money fields with no rounding errors</td>
              <td>Structured <code>{amount, currency}</code> type; decimal-precision arithmetic</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>File upload with drag-and-drop</td>
              <td>FileUpload component with drop zone, MIME filtering, multiple files</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Signature capture</td>
              <td>Canvas-based Signature component with data-URL export</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Pre-populate fields from another system</td>
              <td>Secondary data instances; EHR/CRM/API pre-fill; editable or locked</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Export data in our format (JSON/XML/CSV)</td>
              <td>Bidirectional Mapping DSL with value translation and conditional rules</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Forms that work offline</td>
              <td>Validation and logic run client-side; no server required at runtime</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Same validation on server as client</td>
              <td>Python runtime implements identical FEL evaluation</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Version-lock forms once deployed</td>
              <td>Immutable versioned forms; responses pinned to the version they were filled on</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Migrate old responses to a new form version</td>
              <td>Migration rules: preserve/drop/expression per field</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Route applicants to the right form</td>
              <td>Pre-form screener with FEL routing rules</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Design control (tokens, widgets, layout)</td>
              <td>Theme documents + 37 built-in components; all swappable</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Build forms with AI</td>
              <td>28 MCP tools + conversational chat builder</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>No vendor lock-in</td>
              <td>Open spec, MIT license; definition files are portable JSON</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Static linting before deployment</td>
              <td>Multi-pass Python validator; errors before applicants see the form</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section A: Collecting Data ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Fields</div>
      <h2>13 field types. Every specialized input covered.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        From simple text to structured money amounts — every common data type ships built in.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Text & Numbers</h3>
          <p>Single-line, multi-line, integers, decimals, and URIs. Whitespace normalization (trim, collapse, remove) applied before storage and validation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Dates & Times</h3>
          <p>Date only, date+time, or time only. ISO 8601 storage. Date arithmetic in expressions: difference in years/months/days, component extraction.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Choices</h3>
          <p>Single-select and multi-select, rendered as dropdown, radio group, or checkbox group. Named option lists defined once and reused across fields.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Money</h3>
          <p>Structured <code>{amount, currency}</code> with configurable default currency. String-based amounts eliminate floating-point errors in financial calculations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Files & Signatures</h3>
          <p>File upload with drag-and-drop, MIME type filtering, and multi-file support. Canvas signature component with stroke capture and data-URL export.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Ratings & Sliders</h3>
          <p>Star/icon ratings (configurable icon, optional half-step) and sliders (min/max/step with tick marks).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section B: Smart Form Logic ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">FEL — Formspec Expression Language</div>
      <h2>Calculated fields, conditions, and validation — all in one language.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        FEL is a small, deterministic expression language built into every bind and rule. No code. No plugins. Just formulas.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>61 built-in functions</h3>
          <p>Aggregates (sum, count, avg, min, max), strings, numeric, date/time, logical, type coercion, money, repeat navigation, and state queries. Everything you need for grant calculations, clinical scores, or budget validation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Decimal-precision arithmetic</h3>
          <p>0.1 + 0.2 = 0.3, guaranteed. FEL uses 18-digit decimal semantics, not floating-point. Financial and scientific forms are safe.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Element-wise array math</h3>
          <p><code>sum($items[*].qty * $items[*].price)</code> multiplies each row, then sums. A scalar applied to an array broadcasts automatically — no loops, no code.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Named variables</h3>
          <p>Define <code>@monthlyBudget</code> once at the form level; reference it in a dozen fields. Intermediate values without duplication.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Let expressions</h3>
          <p><code>let x = complex_expr in x + 1</code> for intermediate values within a single formula.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>State queries</h3>
          <p>Ask any field what state it's in: <code>valid($path)</code>, <code>relevant($path)</code>, <code>readonly($path)</code>, <code>required($path)</code>. Use that in other conditions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section C: Conditional Logic ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Binds</div>
      <h2>Show, hide, require, compute — all from a single expression.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Every field, group, or display element can have conditional logic attached. Conditions cascade to children automatically.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>relevant</h3>
          <p>A FEL boolean. When false, the field is hidden, excluded from validation, and omitted from output. A hidden group hides everything inside it. Configurable: remove, empty, or keep hidden data.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>required</h3>
          <p>A FEL expression, not a checkbox. "Required when the user selected nonprofit" is one expression, not a custom rule.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>readonly</h3>
          <p>A FEL expression. A read-only parent locks all children (inherited). Calculated fields are implicitly read-only.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>default</h3>
          <p>A value or expression that populates the field whenever it becomes relevant again. Configurable display for non-relevant fields: hidden or visible-but-locked.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section D: Validation ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Validation</div>
      <h2>Field errors and cross-field business rules — structured, not just red text.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Validation is a data structure you can act on programmatically, not just messages users read.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Field constraints</h3>
          <p>A FEL expression that returns true when the value is valid. <code>constraint</code> + <code>constraintMessage</code>. Works with cross-field references: "end date must be after start date."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Cross-field shapes</h3>
          <p>Named rule sets that target any path in the form. Each shape has a FEL condition, severity (error/warning/info), human-readable message, machine-readable code, and optional activation condition.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Shape composition</h3>
          <p>Compose shapes with <code>and</code>, <code>or</code>, <code>not</code>, and <code>xone</code> (exactly-one). Shapes can activate only when another condition is true (<code>activeWhen</code>).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Structured ValidationReport</h3>
          <p>Every validation run produces a JSON document with a <code>valid</code> flag, per-violation results (path, severity, message, code), counts, and timestamp. Your backend can react to specific codes, not just "the form failed."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Validation timing</h3>
          <p>Per-shape: continuous (every change), on-submit only, or on-demand. Form-wide mode: validate everything, validate on submit, or never.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Three severity levels</h3>
          <p>Error blocks completion; warning flags for review without blocking; info provides context. Warnings surface high-risk patterns without stopping the form.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section E: Navigation & Layout ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Pages & Components</div>
      <h2>Multi-step wizards, tabbed forms, and 37 built-in components.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Full control over navigation and layout — without touching your form logic.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Wizard navigation</h3>
          <p>Step-by-step with Previous/Next/Submit, collapsible side nav, progress indicators (completed/active/upcoming). Per-page validation shows errors in context.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Tab navigation</h3>
          <p>Click-based switching with configurable labels, top or bottom tab bar, and programmatic control.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>37 built-in components</h3>
          <p>Layout (10): Page, Stack, Grid, Columns, Divider, Collapsible, Accordion, Panel, Modal, Popover. Inputs (13): TextInput, NumberInput, Select, Toggle, Checkbox, DatePicker, RadioGroup, CheckboxGroup, Slider, Rating, FileUpload, Signature, MoneyInput. Display (9): Heading, Text, Card, Spacer, Alert, Badge, ProgressBar, Summary, ValidationSummary. Interactive (3): Wizard, Tabs, SubmitButton. Special (2): ConditionalGroup, DataTable.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Theme documents</h3>
          <p>A sidecar JSON file with design tokens, three-level cascade (form → type → field), widget overrides, and CSS class injection. Never touch the form definition to change appearance.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Responsive layout</h3>
          <p>Component tree supports per-breakpoint overrides. Stack vs Grid at different viewport widths without media queries in your theme.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section F: Repeatable Sections ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Repeats</div>
      <h2>Add rows, nest groups, build tables — all from the definition.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Repeatable groups are first-class citizens, not a workaround.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Repeatable groups</h3>
          <p>Any group can become repeatable. Users add and remove instances; minimum and maximum cardinality is validated automatically. Output is a JSON array.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Nested repeats</h3>
          <p>A repeatable group can contain another repeatable group. Medical conditions → medications → dosages. Paths like <code>conditions[2].medications[4].name</code> resolve correctly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Data table</h3>
          <p>A repeatable group rendered as an editable spreadsheet: add/remove row buttons, type-appropriate inputs per column, optional row numbers, computed cells (e.g., line totals).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Repeat navigation in expressions</h3>
          <p><code>@index</code> (1-based row number), <code>@count</code> (total rows), <code>prev()</code>, <code>next()</code>, <code>parent()</code> for navigating between rows in expressions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section G: Data In, Data Out ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Integration</div>
      <h2>Pre-fill from any source. Export to any format.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Formspec is the hub — data flows in from your existing systems and out to wherever it needs to go.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Secondary data instances</h3>
          <p>Declare named data sources (inline JSON, external URL, or host-provided function). Pre-populate fields with <code>prePopulate</code>; mark as editable or locked. Reference instances in FEL expressions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Named option lists</h3>
          <p>Define a choice list once (<code>optionSets</code>), reference it across multiple fields. Update one list; all fields pick it up.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Mapping DSL</h3>
          <p>A separate JSON document that transforms Formspec responses into external schemas. Three output formats: JSON (restructure and rename), XML (namespaces, attributes, CDATA), CSV (configurable delimiter, encoding, header).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Bidirectional transforms</h3>
          <p>The same mapping can import and export. <code>valueMap</code> translates internal codes to external codes and back. Conditional rules skip fields when a guard expression is false.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Reversibility guarantees</h3>
          <p><code>preserve</code> transforms are always reversible. <code>coerce</code> is reversible for lossless type pairs. <code>valueMap</code> is reversible when one-to-one. Non-reversible transforms require an explicit reverse override.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section H: Form Lifecycle ─── -->
    <section class="features-section">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Versioning</div>
      <h2>Version-locked forms. Response pinning. Formal migrations.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        When regulated industries change a form, they need answers: what was the user shown? which version? can existing responses still be validated? Formspec answers all three.
      </p>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Immutable versions</h3>
          <p>Once published ("active"), a form version is immutable. Any change produces a new version. Definitions carry a stable URL + version identity pair.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Response pinning</h3>
          <p>Every submitted response records the exact version it was filled against. Validation always uses the pinned version — never a newer one.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Formal migrations</h3>
          <p>Field-by-field mapping from prior versions: <code>preserve</code> (carry value as-is), <code>drop</code> (discard), or <code>expression</code> (compute new value via FEL). Migration produces a new response; the original is preserved.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Changelog format</h3>
          <p>Atomic diffs between versions with impact classification (breaking/compatible/cosmetic) and <code>semverImpact</code> for CI/CD gates.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Screener routing</h3>
          <p>A pre-form screener with its own fields and FEL routing rules sits before the main form. First-match routing: emergency → emergency intake; urgent → urgent care; everyone else → standard intake.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ─── Section I: Authoring ─── -->
    <section class="features-section features-section--last">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Build it</div>
      <h2>Three ways to build. All produce the same JSON.</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Whether you prefer visual tools, conversation, or AI-assisted authoring — the output is the same portable JSON specification.
      </p>
      <div class="authoring-grid">
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Formspec Studio</h3>
          <p>A full visual authoring environment with 7 workspace tabs: Editor (drag-drop structure), Logic (rules and calculations), Data (option lists and instances), Pages (wizard/tab order), Theme (design tokens and cascade), Mapping (export transforms), Preview (live preview with viewport switcher). Blueprint sidebar, command palette (Cmd+K), undo/redo.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>Chat builder</h3>
          <p>Describe what you need in plain language. A conversational interface updates a live preview alongside the conversation. Runs on your choice of AI provider.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="feature-card">
          <h3>AI tool integration (MCP)</h3>
          <p>28 structured tools for AI assistants. Add fields, set rules, configure validation shapes, manage routing and navigation, query and audit, undo/redo — all through structured tool calls that validate before they write.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <CallToAction />
  </article>
</Page>

<style>
  .features {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
  }

  .features-header {
    padding: 5rem clamp(1.25rem, 4vw, 2.5rem) 3rem;
    max-width: 72rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .features-header h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 2.75rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .features-lead {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 48rem;
  }

  .section-eyebrow {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .features-section {
    max-width: 72rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem clamp(1.25rem, 4vw, 2.5rem);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .features-section--last {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  .features-section h2 {
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2.5vw, 1.875rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .section-lead {
    font-size: 1.0625rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
    max-width: 48rem;
  }

  /* ─── BLUF Table ─── */

  .table-wrap {
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
  }

  .bluf-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .bluf-table th {
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    color: var(--color-ink-tertiary);
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--color-border-strong);
  }

  .bluf-table td {
    padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .bluf-table td:first-child {
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .bluf-table tbody tr:nth-child(even) {
    background: var(--color-surface-raised);
  }

  .bluf-table tbody tr:hover {
    background: var(--color-accent-light);
  }

  .bluf-table code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    background: var(--color-surface-raised);
    padding: 0.125rem 0.375rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
  }

  /* ─── Feature Cards ─── */

  .feature-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  .feature-card {
    background: var(--color-surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: 1.5rem;
    transition: border-color 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s;
  }

  .feature-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-border-strong);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);
  }

  .feature-card h3 {
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-ink);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .feature-card p {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-secondary);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .feature-card code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.8125rem;
    background: var(--color-surface-raised);
    padding: 0.1rem 0.35rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
  }

  /* ─── Authoring Grid (3-col) ─── */

  .authoring-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }

  /* ─── Mobile ─── */

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .feature-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .authoring-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .bluf-table td:first-child {
      white-space: normal;
    }
  }
</style>
